column95:
For the purposes of enhancing and bench-marking our operations and in particular quality of learning/ teaching, we have scheduled visits to National and top schools like Maseno School and Chemelil Academy in the region and peers with known dependable academic culture like St. Stephen Minara Seconday School. This week-long programme often involve teachers moderation and co-teaching and testing of students as well as co-curricula activities. 

Boys participate in competitive inter-school events, organized bilateral visits and diversified   mentoring talks that recognizes and support the broad base that the students hail from.  Bristtol School is a multi-tribe centre that espouse commonality respecting and accommodating all. Besides, the foregoing, Bristtol School organizes exchange tests and mocks that are externally moderated and marked. This is complemented by external examiner moderation and teaching. The composite of these together with internal controls and peer review, has served to sharpen academics at Bristtol School.

column98: Firstly, we ask parents to identify SEN pupils on entry.  We recommend SEN experts outside the school to parents, and our Heads of Faculty ensure that pupils are assisted, where possible, according to these experts' confidential recommendations.  In preparation for the permitted extra time, etc., that IGCSE SEN pupils may sometimes be permitted at the end of their careers, we enable such pupils to have extended papers throughout the school. We are also able to offer scribes, etc., where required.  We expect all lessons to incorporate differentiation in the planning, for the benefit of 'struggling' SEN pupils, but also the gifted and talented, where these are enrolled.  We develop particular relationships with the parents of SEN pupils.

column11: I have dual functions in the school. I head the Linguistics  Department, which incorporates First Language English ,  English as a Second Language,Kiswahili, French, and Literature in English.  I am also the Head of Careers. As Head of Linguistics, I supervise curriculum delivery in my docket and ensure that subject teachers attend lessons promptly, keep professional records and generally abide by the ethos of the teaching  profession and the culture of the school. As Head of Careers, I liaise with higher learning institutions to ensure that students identify their career aspirations, and expose them to talks by academics, university representatives and industry practitioners for purposes of placement and mentorship. Besides, I am a teacher of English and Literature.
column12: Head of Linguistics and Careers Advisor
column45: My students come from diverse backgrounds. Thus, I invite industry professionals sand tertiary institutions, and academic and non-academic experts from diverse backgrounds to give talks to students every Wednesday for two hours. We have so far hosted university reps and academics from the United States, Japan,Canada, UK,Australia,Switzerland and Kenya. column36: As a school, we believe that business and entrepreneurship skills are horned early. Since 2016 we commenced a programme to educate pupils hands on on maize and business farming. We chose on the two crops because they are grown in the community and children as they grow need to understand the agronomic practices in a practical sense. We set aside a piece of land (plot) where the children carry out the activities. Every year since 2016, we organize for children to visit the banking sector to understand the banking process as well as interact with bank officials. In 2017 and 2018, the banking visit coincided with Global Money Week, and we use the opportunity to train children about money and its use to their level of understanding. This year, pupils of grade 4 to 6 level participated in kale growing as a business and the school purchased from the pupils and teachers and other staff provided market for the vegetables. At the end of the year they made Ksh 4,500 from their vegetable sales.

column42: For the second year running The Kibabii Academy engages in the School Enterprise Challenge. It is a global business competition for primary and high school students. column21: We've started putting up permanent classes which ensures that the children/pupils are protected from natural hazards like dust,intense sunlight, wind and other harsh climatic conditions.We stick to maximum intake per class to avoid congestion and overcrowding(30 pupils per class), the windows are standardized to ensure there is sufficient ventilation, the doors are opened from outside per the ministry regulation policy.Two teachers are engaged to be on duty every day to check on the safety of all the pupils.Teachers accompany learners for co-curricular activities to check on safety in the pitch and to ensure any accident in the field is given due attention and the players first Aid solution.
column22: The school has two exit doors for evacuation in case of a disaster.Two teachers are being trained on first aid and how to handle emergency issues and natural disasters.School buildings strictly follow the approved architectural designs, the head teacher is the custodian of daily  occurence  book to take note and act on key risky areas.We have enough well trained teachers who can take quick action to save a situation
column27: N/A because it is a day school Currently.
column29: Professionals from the ministry of education and Public health are invited at least twice a term to give their advice and views on safety.Frequent meetings is held with staff to review safety issues especially in all the classes.The school has employed enough security officers to patrol and report on any security breach.The school is also in the process of introducing enough Fire extinguishers and cctv cameras in key areas. During meetings and academic days the management is planning to introduce proper screening at the gate for all the visitors to weed out terrorists.More teachers will also be taken for training in security and safety.

column36: We encourage pupils/Students to learn entrepreneurial skills early in life.As the adage goes"you cannot teach an old dog new tricks" our school realizes that children have different talents and gifts which are important for one's career.These must be taught early so that the pupil can focus and build on future career .Entrepreneurial skills are also important for students who will secure employment because a single income is never enough.The school has a program to invite a motivational speaker on entrepreneurship at least once a term.This encourages the pupils to be critical thinkers who can come up with great ideas

column21: We have a Health and Safety committee that takes a lead role in guiding the school in all matters related to Health and Safety. This is in accordance with the functions of schools health and safety policies outlined in the Safety Standards Manual for Schools in Kenya. The committee carries out periodical risk assessments of the whole school structures and equipment and advices the Facility and Maintenance department accordingly. The committee organizes safety training and emergency drills for the school community.

column29:
The school environs are kept spotlessly clean and safe for all our students with special attention to the work and play areas and equipment. The classrooms and all other areas that students often occupy are also well maintained. The restricted areas are well marked. 
Rusinga Schools to a large measure implement existing safety and security policies and procedures. These include:
Security Policy that for example outlines the day to day procedures of manning ingress and egress points in the school.
Health and Safety Policy that summarizes the Schools role in keeping a safe environment free of occupational hazards.
Child Protection Policy that describes the schools commitment to safeguarding all children under its care.
Anti-bullying Policy which states the schools zero tolerance stance on bullying. 
We also a zero tolerance drug free zone. This is directed by a policy that is mandatory for all students to sign on entry into grade eight. 
We also hold periodic Mental Health awareness sessions (organized by our resident School Counsellor) for both parents and students as well as health camps set up in School to check basic health status.
The anti-drugs campaign is one way that the school ensures that our students are not only informed but convinced to make the right choices in life. SCAD programmes are set up once every 2-3 years to guide students from 13-16 years of age on drug awareness. 
The school has a well-equipped sick bay manned by two qualified pediatrics nurses. In case of emergencies needing evacuation to hospital, the school has contracted AAR ambulance services 
Rusinga also runs a Chaplaincy office that spearheads Pastoral programmes designed for members of the community at all levels. Collaborations with churches are in place to help in Christian spiritual grounding for all.
Rusinga Schools run a Community Service club which engages the local community in various charitable programmes like market clean-up. For this reason, building strong bonds between the school and the community around ensures child safety in and out of school.
column36:
The School normally holds Annual Business Day every October. The event is meant to crystallise the business concepts learned in class. The Business Day allows our learners to come up with business proposal/plans and implement them. They appreciate the risks and rewards of running a business, the importance of health and safety and record keeping. This event is held for both our Primary and Senior School students.
This forum has been a launching pad for many business start-ups by our own students e.g.  One of our Alumni, runs a beauty and fashion line and the idea was incubated at Rusinga when she used to run a salon and massage parlour during the business days. She is now a beauty business woman in her own right and has been has been featured in one of our dailies.

column58:
Leadership kicks off in the early years. This is done on a rotational basis to give every learner a chance to lead.  In the later years, from Year 3, School Prefects are elected every year through applying for the positions, stating what they will bring in. Free and fair elections of the short-listed candidates is conducted through the secret ballot from Prep School through to Senior School. Senior School has also adopted a system of Prefect Emeritus, where the outgoing Head Girl and Boy mentor the incoming Prefects body. This body presents its proposal on school improvement to the senior management and many different developments to the school programmes have been initiated by the Prefect body. They also help manage student adherence to the School Code of Conduct. The senior prefects also run the senior school assemblies where they make announcements and manage various activities. They also manage wider school events like Praise and Prize Day in ushering and maintaining general order.
The Students Council is another leadership body that comprises class representatives from all classes. Class Reps are elected at Class level from Year 3 to Year 13. In Senior School, however, the class reps also form the Students Council body from which they elect their Council President and the governing committee. The sole aim of this group is to advance school improvement at grass-root level. We encourage the student voice to be heard through these organs.
House Captains are elected largely by popular vote by their housemates to run inter-house affairs such as inter-house sports and athletics, swimming gala and inter-house co-curricular competitions across the School.
Leadership workshops and seminars for all student leaders from Prep to Senior school to strengthen their leadership potential and to equip them with leadership knowledge are scheduled for the student leadership teams every year.

column68:
Many students present proposals for CSR and engage the whole school in fundraising activities to complete projects earmarked by the students themselves. They have on-going projects that successive students continue with. 
For example, one of the projects the students support is a primary school within the environs with play equipment and mattresses for the Kindergarteners, books, stationery and building ongoing mentorship for more senior primary school children. The school reports to us that enrolment has gone up owing to Rusinga students support for the school. 
Rusinga Schools run a Community Service club which engages the local community in various charitable programmes like market clean-up.
Our students also host other children from disadvantaged environments at Rusinga during Easter and Christmas seasons to share the spirit of the two seasons.
We also have a student led charity programme to the Prayers Beyond Boundaries Homecare Centre in Maai Mahiu, Naivasha.
One of our alumnus went ahead to develop a pads initiative with a CSR component after she graduated with a Bachelors Degree in Business.   Many continue to serve in CSR initiatives after leaving Rusinga.
These and more helps the school live out its corporate social responsibility and building strong bonds between the school and the community around.

We train our learners to be job creators rather than job seekers. We offer business studies as a subject to all learners at all levels. We have different clubs which are run as businesses  and the members of each club generate income from their respective clubs. 
Our business club participate in Junior Achievement Company  programme in high schools. In this programme, the students  run a company and compete at the end of the year with more that 40 schools. 
Each and every year we offer business and entrepreneurship training to our form four students after completing their KSCE exams where they are trained on how to successfully start and run a business, write a business plan and how to fund the business.

column11:
Crawford International School is a trailblazer in innovative and forward-thinking education. Every student is acknowledged and offered the opportunity to excel. The mottos Every Child a Masterpiece and Commitment to Excellence underpins all. The child-centred approach ensures that our students examine and realise their own potential.

Crawford International School offers an academic foundation of the highest order and ensures that each student is developed into a fully-rounded individual whilst being skilled to interact in a collaborative manner. Cultural success in Arts, Music, Dance and Drama, is a cornerstone of the education that we provide, while sport is enjoyed by every sports-loving student and community involvement is celebrated by every civic-minded citizen.

column21:
The Crawford International school is secure place for learning.

We have security team that manages the school security detail and that which ensures all is well when coming and out.

People and vehicles are screened  before coming in and as they leave.

The school has an extensive CCTV network which ensures that every weird activity monitored and safety of all is addressed.

The access control at the boarding facility only allows those who are boarding to have access to the facility.

Then there is security representative around major blocks to ensure that any safety event is reported immediately and addressed.

The school has lifts for the first floor for the disabled students.

The fire alarm systems are also provided and fire assembly points clearly stipulated.

The cable system is well done to ensure that students and anyone is safe for learning process.

There are fans in all classes to  provide good aeration during lessons .

There are also clear walk-ways  for the student and other staff for safety.

The school has a school Nurse and ambulances services are provided by Red Cross and AAR care.

The swimming pool instructors and other staff members are all trained on first aid and life saving skills.

Crawford is safe for every one.

column36: We have business themed week that encourages learners to come up with business ideas. The learners are then expected to come up with their own brands, products and strategy and pitch them to potential investors who we invited during the presentations.
column38: We have clubs such as: MSUN , Wajibika...the role of the clubs are to propose  solutions to global issues and the key aspect focuses on addressing poverty. The learners use bake sales as a way of raising money and helping the less fortunate, the disabled or secure long term projects such as borehole drilling or donating money for eye surgery.  On some occasions the bakes sales are held by all students to sell their own supplies i.e. cakes, lemonade and others.
column42: Our competitions are held at either house team levels or class.
column45:
They attend career fairs/ university exhibitions. 

The school has hosted career talks from different 'influencers'. We have invited county officials, directors of universities and strong established companies to motivate our learners by sharing their journey towards choosing their careers. 

We have also identified self made brands by individuals who have managed to use their skills from university to create businesses and employment for citizens. Our World Scholar's Club (WSC) has also seen some of our students visit Yale University and share a platform with international students and lecturers enabling them to exchange experiences and ask questions.
column58: We elect the school student body through an election vote process that takes place in two days. Students are expected to pick a paper that includes different levels of leadership. They are then expected to tick against which potential leader they find favorable for the position. The paper is then dropped into a sealed ballot box that is tallied by the teachers and winners announced.
column66: We communicate to parents through the school diary which is owned by each student. The teacher records any event or comment of the day so that parents are updated about what the students are up-to in school. It is clear to parents that the diary should be checked on a daily record. For serious issues the head or teacher is allowed to reach the parent directly through phone call to set up meetings .We also used official mails.
column67: The parents have access  to the relevant class teachers contacts . We also use whats app groups for each class to address broader class issues affecting all students. To update parents or remind them of upcoming events.
